But apart from the fact that there is little early or positive evidence that the library was really established, there are one or two circumstances which confirm rather than allay our doubts. We have seen that De Bury actually died in debt, and we know that his executore sold at least some portion of his books. It has already been noticed that de Chambre says nothing of alibrary at Oxford3 and the language of Leland is quite consistent with the idea of a scheme that was never carried into effect. If now we look into the xixth chapter of the Philobiblon‚ we find that in the best MSS, instead of naming the Hall to which his books are to be presented, the Bishop leaves a capital letter N in the text—which was the common fashion of indicating a place left for the insertion of a proper name. In the xviiith chapter he speaks of his long nonrished design of founding a Hall, but so as clearly to imply that this intention had yet to be fnlfilled-and it must be remembered that De Bury died less than four months after finishing the Philobiblon.
